<br>
Scanning the shadows, eyes never resting and making it difficult to tell what he does see and what remains hidden, the half elf moves to the bar, hoping for gypsy wine, but deciding that perhaps his favored refreshment may be too light-hearted for this hall...he settles for red.<br>
<br>
As he enters the room completely and stands at the bar, a graceful-necked lute is visible slung upon his back, a bulge at his right side reveals a pouch beneath his cloak. Turning from the bar, the bard looks again over the room, the odd mix of human and elvish features casting his age into question...eyes glinting with a hint of mischief could belong to a boy of twelve, but the crinkles around them belie that youth...<br>
<br>
Clearing his throat and raising his glass, the singer speaks, a voice hovering between tenor and baritone that wraps around his words with the trained timbre of a master singer. <br>
<br>
&quot;Greetings, Shadow Guard, lords and ladies of this hall. I thank you for your hospitality and this fine wine; a better vintage than I would have expected to be served to first-time guests.&quot;<br>
<br>
Taking an appreciative sip from his glass, he continues.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have heard your names voiced among another group...the Nefastus Deus, with whom I have recently, and quite by chance, come into contact. Your High Assassin quite caught my ear with verse and verbal artistry,&quot; he inclines his head respectfully, though not in any particular direction, &quot;that I am certain he mirrors in blood and blade. I have come to hear more, if there is more to be heard, and perhaps to share a song or two as well, should you wish it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Leaning back a bit and resting his elbow upon the bar, the musician smiles again, cradling the glass in his hand, oddly comfortable in the room...Perhaps his history among the Teir'dal in his own realm would offer sustenance here as well.<br>
<br>
___<br>
<br>
Keats Lovesonnet<br>
Sigil of the Silver Tongue<br>
Grand Sigil of the Wayfarers<br>
